      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Moment Preserved</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Hal Glatzer letter on Herbert Muschamp's June 25 article notes many examples of architecture from 1931 International Colonial Expo are on view at Musee des Annees 30 in Boulogne-Billancourt, France (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>While the architecture of the 1931 International Colonial Exposition [''Colonial Fantasies: When the Empire Has No Clothes'' by Herbert Muschamp, June 25] is long gone, visitors to Paris can still judge for themselves the merits of the ''colonial'' artworks that were exhibited there. Many of the pictures and sculptures -- especially those most celebrated at the time -- are in the permanent collection of the Musee des Annees 30 (the Museum of the 1930's), in the Paris suburb of Boulogne-Billancourt.</p>
        <p>HAL GLATZER  San Francisco</p>
      </block>
